# 🌌 GNOME Live Wallpaper Engine

Turn your static GNOME desktop into a dynamic experience. This extension uses **mpv** to play videos, GIFs, and WebM files seamlessly as your background—fully optimized for both **Wayland** and **X11**.

---

## ✨ Features

- 🎬 **Integrated Gallery:** Browse and select your wallpapers directly from the GNOME Settings.
- 📥 **Smart Import:** Add videos with a single click. The extension automatically cleans filenames and clones them into your local library.
- 👻 **Ghost-Mode:** Clicks and keypresses pass through the video to your desktop icons. The wallpaper stays on the bottom layer (DESKTOP).
- 📐 **No Black Bars:** Uses Panscan logic to zoom and fill your screen perfectly, regardless of the video aspect ratio.
- 🚀 **GPU Optimized:** Supports hardware acceleration (hwdec=auto) to ensure your system stays fast and responsive.
- 🔄 **Live Updates:** Switching a wallpaper in the gallery applies the change to your desktop instantly.

---

## 🛠 Prerequisites

You must have **mpv** installed on your system for the engine to work:

# Ubuntu / Zorin OS / Debian

sudo apt update && sudo apt install mpv

# Fedora

sudo dnf install mpv

# Arch Linux

sudo pacman -S mpv

---

## 🚀 Installation

### 1. Folder Naming (CRITICAL)

The extension folder **MUST** be named exactly:
gnome-wallpaper-engine@gjs.com

### 2. Move to Extensions Directory

# Clone the repository

git clone https://github.com/achu94/gnome-wallpaper-engine.git

# Create directory

mkdir -p ~/.local/share/gnome-shell/extensions/

# Move and rename correctly

cp -r gnome-wallpaper-engine ~/.local/share/gnome-shell/extensions/gnome-wallpaper-engine@gjs.com

### 3. Compile GSettings Schemas

The settings won't open unless you compile the schemas:

cd ~/.local/share/gnome-shell/extensions/gnome-wallpaper-engine@gjs.com
glib-compile-schemas schemas/

### 4. Restart & Enable

- Wayland (Zorin/Ubuntu): Log out and log back in.
- X11: Press Alt+F2, type 'r', and hit Enter.
- Enable the extension using the "Extensions" app.

---

## 📖 How to Use

1. Open the Extension Settings.
2. Click "Add Video/GIF" to import your favorite loops.
3. Select a thumbnail from the gallery.
4. Start the engine via the Panel Indicator (top-right corner).

